# Walkthrough: Algorithmic Map Prototype

I have implemented the core backend for the **Algorithmic Map** feature, enabling `Dissect` to scan the entire repository and generate an "Algorithm Inventory".

## Changes Implemented

### 1. Dynamic Complexity Analysis
Updated [dissect/detectors/quicksort.py](file:///home/kuro/Documents/Dissect/dissect/detectors/quicksort.py) to calculate time complexity dynamically based on AST depth and recursion patterns, rather than returning "Unknown" or static values.

### 2. Algorithm Scanner
Created [dissect/scanner.py](file:///home/kuro/Documents/Dissect/dissect/scanner.py), which:
- Recursively walks the directory tree.
- Filters out ignored directories (`.git`, `node_modules`, etc.).
- Parses [.py](file:///home/kuro/Documents/Dissect/build.py), `.js`, and `.java` files.
- Runs all registered detectors on every function.

### 3. CLI Command
Added a new [map](file:///home/kuro/Documents/Dissect/dissect/cli.py#12-22) command to the CLI.

```bash
# Scan current directory and save to default JSON
dissect map --dir .

# Scan specific folder and output to custom file
dissect map --dir ./src --output inventory.json
```

### 4. Output Format
The [map](file:///home/kuro/Documents/Dissect/dissect/cli.py#12-22) command generates a JSON inventory:

```json
{
  "meta": {
    "root": ".",
    "total_files": 15,
    "algorithms_found": 3
  },
  "files": [
    {
      "path": "src/sort.py",
      "functions": [
        {
          "name": "quick_sort",
          "line": 12,
          "algorithms": [
            {
              "type": "Quicksort",
              "confidence": 0.85,
              "complexity": "O(n log n)",  <-- New!
              "category": "sorting"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

